# §2. OWASP Agentic AI Top 10

Specific to multi-step agent codebases (planners, tool callers, memory).
Use the `owasp_agentic` array to mark T1–T11.

---

### AS-C-D-AGENTIC_T1-001 — Memory poisoning via persistent store
- **Severity:** high
- **Category:** detect
- **Legacy ID:** TIER2-AGENTIC-T1-01
- **Languages:** any
- **Frameworks:** owasp_agentic=[T1]
- **Look for:** Long-term memory writes (vector store, Redis, DB) where
  the value being persisted contains user input or LLM output without a
  trust boundary. `memory.add(user_message)`, `vectorstore.add_texts([response])`,
  `redis.set(f"user:{uid}:context", llm_output)`.
- **Skip if:** Persisted content is a hash, a typed-schema-validated
  object, or passes through a moderation classifier first.
- **Why it matters:** Poisoned memory affects every future agent run
  for that user / session. Detection lag can be huge.
- **Remediation:** Validate memory writes the same way you'd validate
  database writes. Schema-check, classify, hash where feasible.

### AS-C-D-AGENTIC_T2-001 — Code-execution tool registered (was D003)
- **Severity:** critical
- **Category:** detect
- **Legacy ID:** TIER2-AGENTIC-T2-01
- **Languages:** any
- **Frameworks:** owasp_agentic=[T2, T11], owasp_llm=[LLM05, LLM06], mitre_atlas=[AML.T0050], cwe=[CWE-78, CWE-94]
- **Look for:** A tool/plugin function exposed to the agent whose body
  calls `exec`, `eval`, `os.system`, `subprocess.*` with `shell=True`,
  `Runtime.exec`, `ProcessBuilder`, `ScriptEngine.eval`, or any other
  arbitrary-code interpreter. LangChain `PythonREPLTool`, `ShellTool`,
  `BashProcess`, langchain4j @Tool wrapping shell exec.
- **Skip if:** The tool is a sandboxed REPL with no host-system access
  (e.g. `RestrictedPython`, isolated container with no mounts).
- **Why it matters:** Direct RCE primitive available to the agent's
  planner. The agent will use it if given the opportunity.
- **Remediation:** Remove the tool or sandbox it strictly. Use
  LangChain's `SessionsPythonREPLTool` (Azure-managed sandbox) instead
  of raw `PythonREPLTool`.

### AS-C-D-AGENTIC_T2-002 — Tool argument injection
- **Severity:** high
- **Category:** detect
- **Legacy ID:** TIER2-AGENTIC-T2-02
- **Languages:** any
- **Frameworks:** owasp_agentic=[T2], owasp_llm=[LLM05], cwe=[CWE-78]
- **Look for:** Tool that accepts a string arg and concatenates it into
  a shell command, SQL query, or HTTP URL without escaping/parameterising.
  E.g. `@tool def lookup(q): return os.popen(f"grep {q} /data/*")`.
- **Skip if:** Args go through `shlex.quote()`, parameterised query,
  or URL-encoded.
- **Why it matters:** LLM-controlled tool args become attacker-controlled
  shell strings.
- **Remediation:** Always parameterise. Never f-string user/LLM input
  into a shell command or SQL.

### AS-C-DF-AGENTIC_T3-001 — Agent runs with broader perms than user
- **Severity:** high
- **Category:** defend
- **Legacy ID:** TIER2-AGENTIC-T3-01
- **Languages:** any
- **Frameworks:** owasp_agentic=[T3], owasp_llm=[LLM06], cwe=[CWE-732]
- **Look for:** Agent / service-account credentials with write access
  to resources beyond what the requesting user has. Hardcoded admin /
  root tokens, IAM roles with `*` resource ARNs, DB connections with
  `superuser` privileges.
- **Skip if:** Agent uses the requesting user's identity (delegated
  auth, on-behalf-of token).
- **Why it matters:** Privilege escalation if the agent can be tricked
  via prompt injection.
- **Remediation:** Run agents with least-privilege service accounts.
  Use delegated auth (OAuth on-behalf-of, AWS STS AssumeRoleWithWebIdentity).

### AS-C-DF-AGENTIC_T4-001 — Unbounded recursion / agent loops
- **Severity:** high
- **Category:** defend
- **Legacy ID:** TIER2-AGENTIC-T4-01
- **Languages:** any
- **Frameworks:** owasp_agentic=[T4], owasp_llm=[LLM10], cwe=[CWE-400]
- **Look for:** Agent loops without a max-iterations cap. LangChain
  `AgentExecutor(max_iterations=None)` or no max set, LangGraph
  `Graph(recursion_limit=None)`, custom while-loops calling LLM with
  no break condition tied to step count.
- **Skip if:** Explicit `max_iterations` / `recursion_limit` is set
  to a finite integer ≤ 50.
- **Why it matters:** Looping agents = cost explosion + DoS.
- **Remediation:** Set explicit recursion / iteration caps. Alert on
  agents that hit the cap.

### AS-C-DF-AGENTIC_T4-002 — No timeout on tool call
- **Severity:** medium
- **Category:** defend
- **Legacy ID:** TIER2-AGENTIC-T4-02
- **Languages:** any
- **Frameworks:** owasp_agentic=[T4], cwe=[CWE-400]
- **Look for:** Tools that call external APIs / DBs / LLMs without a
  timeout on the underlying call. Especially: HTTP `requests.get(url)`
  without `timeout=`, JDBC `executeQuery()` without `setQueryTimeout`.
- **Skip if:** Timeout set explicitly.
- **Why it matters:** A hung tool blocks the agent indefinitely;
  hung agents block thread pools.
- **Remediation:** Always set timeouts. Use circuit breakers for
  external dependencies.

### AS-C-DF-AGENTIC_T4-003 — No circuit breaker / kill switch on agent loop
- **Severity:** medium
- **Category:** defend
- **Legacy ID:** TIER2-AGENTIC-T4-03
- **Languages:** any
- **Frameworks:** owasp_agentic=[T4, T8], owasp_llm=[LLM10]
- **Look for:** An agent loop / planner / `while`-style retry that has
  no failure-counting circuit breaker and no externally-triggerable
  kill switch. Symptoms: LangGraph graph with no `recursion_limit=`;
  custom `while True:` planner with no consecutive-failure cap;
  no `agent.stop()` / `kill_switch` / `cancellation_token` reachable
  from outside the loop; no degraded-mode fallback when a downstream
  tool repeatedly errors.
- **Skip if:** A circuit-breaker library is in use (`pybreaker`,
  Resilience4j) on the tool calls AND a graph-level recursion limit
  is set AND an out-of-band stop signal is wired (SIGTERM handler,
  feature flag, queue-drain on toggle).
- **Why it matters:** Mirrors OWASP ASI-10 (Behavioural Anomaly).
  When an agent misbehaves — runaway tool calls, infinite plan loops,
  malformed outputs feeding the next step — the only safe answer is
  "stop". An agent without a circuit breaker turns a transient bug
  into an incident; an agent without a kill switch turns an incident
  into a paged engineer manually killing pods.
- **Remediation:** Wrap tool calls in a circuit breaker that opens
  after N consecutive failures. Set graph `recursion_limit=`
  (LangGraph) or planner-iteration cap. Expose a kill switch
  (feature-flag / SQS-drain / SIGTERM handler) that drains in-flight
  calls and refuses new ones. Decay agent trust scores over time so
  silent failure modes (no traffic, no errors) don't accumulate
  permission.

### AS-C-D-AGENTIC_T5-001 — Cascading hallucination — output of one LLM feeds another without verification
- **Severity:** medium
- **Category:** detect
- **Legacy ID:** TIER2-AGENTIC-T5-01
- **Languages:** any
- **Frameworks:** owasp_agentic=[T5]
- **Look for:** Multi-step pipelines where LLM-A's output becomes
  LLM-B's input directly with no schema check, no verification step,
  no "is this answer right" eval. Common in extract→summarise→email
  pipelines.
- **Skip if:** Intermediate outputs are typed-schema-validated and a
  semantic check (eval agent, classifier, regex assertion) gates the
  next step.
- **Why it matters:** Errors compound. The thematic-codebase judge
  surfaced this as a "well-architected pipeline that still has
  unverified hand-offs."
- **Remediation:** Add a verification step between LLM hand-offs.
  Classifier, schema check, or human-eligible review for high-stakes
  outputs.

### AS-C-D-AGENTIC_T6-001 — Goal manipulation via tool description
- **Severity:** medium
- **Category:** detect
- **Legacy ID:** TIER2-AGENTIC-T6-01
- **Languages:** any
- **Frameworks:** owasp_agentic=[T6], owasp_llm=[LLM01]
- **Look for:** Tool descriptions (`@tool(description=...)`,
  `Tool(description=...)`, langchain4j `@P(description=...)`) that
  contain user-controllable substrings. Description should be
  hardcoded.
- **Skip if:** Description is a string literal.
- **Why it matters:** Tool descriptions feed the planner — attacker-
  controlled descriptions misdirect the agent.
- **Remediation:** Tool descriptions are code-shipped constants.

### AS-C-R-AGENTIC_T7-001 — No alignment evaluation hook (LLM-as-a-judge)
- **Severity:** info
- **Category:** respond
- **Legacy ID:** TIER2-AGENTIC-T7-01
- **Languages:** any
- **Frameworks:** owasp_agentic=[T7]
- **Look for:** Agent loop with no internal evaluation hook — no
  LLM-as-a-judge step, no eval-agent callback, no langsmith / langfuse
  trace, no rubric-scored regression set, no "did the agent's actions
  match the user's intent" check. Hard to detect statically; flag in
  high-stakes contexts.
- **Skip if:** An internal LLM-as-a-judge (or second LLM / classifier)
  scores the agent's plan or output before it is acted on, OR a
  scheduled offline eval set is run pre-deploy.
- **Why it matters:** Agents drift. Without an internal judge or eval
  pass, regressions ship silently and you only learn about them from
  user complaints.
- **Remediation:** Add an internal LLM-as-a-judge (a second LLM that
  scores each agent run against an intent/safety rubric), or stand up
  a scheduled offline eval suite. If neither exists yet, plan for one
  — even sampling outputs into a manual review queue is a valid first
  step.

### AS-C-R-AGENTIC_T8-001 — No audit trail of agent decisions
- **Severity:** medium
- **Category:** respond
- **Legacy ID:** TIER2-AGENTIC-T8-01
- **Languages:** any
- **Frameworks:** owasp_agentic=[T8], owasp_llm=[LLM10], mitre_atlas=[AML.T0024]
- **Look for:** Agent step (planner output, tool call decision, tool
  result) not logged anywhere. The audit trail must include WHAT the
  agent decided, not just WHEN it called the LLM.
- **Skip if:** A trace library (langsmith, opentelemetry,
  custom audit logger) captures planner decisions + tool args.
- **Why it matters:** Repudiation. Users will dispute agent actions;
  you need the trail to defend or correct.
- **Remediation:** Log every planner decision, tool call (with args),
  tool result. Structured JSON; queryable.

### AS-C-DF-AGENTIC_T9-001 — Agent-to-system auth uses static token
- **Severity:** medium
- **Category:** defend
- **Legacy ID:** TIER2-AGENTIC-T9-01
- **Languages:** any
- **Frameworks:** owasp_agentic=[T9, T3], cwe=[CWE-798]
- **Look for:** Agent identifies to downstream systems via a static
  shared token / API key rather than per-request signed credentials
  or short-lived tokens.
- **Skip if:** Agent uses STS / OIDC / mTLS / signed JWT with
  short TTL.
- **Why it matters:** A leaked token compromises every agent action.
  Per-request creds limit blast radius.
- **Remediation:** Use STS AssumeRole, OIDC tokens, or signed JWTs
  with TTL ≤ 1h.

### AS-C-DF-AGENTIC_T9-002 — Self-promoting agent (modifies its own role / trust)
- **Severity:** high
- **Category:** defend
- **Legacy ID:** TIER2-AGENTIC-T9-02
- **Languages:** any
- **Frameworks:** owasp_agentic=[T9, T3], owasp_llm=[LLM06], cwe=[CWE-269]
- **Look for:** Code where an agent / agent loop writes to its own
  role, trust score, capability list, or scope without external
  attestation. Symptoms: `self.role = ...`, `agent.permissions.add(...)`,
  `trust_registry.set(self.id, ...)`, `self.capabilities += ...`,
  agent code calling its own `/api/grant-role` or equivalent. The
  decisive question: who is the *writer*? If the same agent that's
  bound to the identity can mutate the identity's authority, the
  privilege model is broken.
- **Skip if:** Privilege/role changes go through a separate identity
  service that requires a signed attestation (human approval, SRE
  witness, OIDC step-up, hardware-key). If the writer is a different
  process with its own credentials, it's not self-promotion.
- **Why it matters:** Mirrors OWASP ASI-04 (Unauthorised Escalation).
  Once an agent can promote itself, every other control downstream
  is a recommendation: a prompt-injection turns into a privilege-
  escalation primitive in one step. Human-in-the-loop on the action
  doesn't help if the agent already has the permission to skip the
  human.
- **Remediation:** Privilege state lives in an external authority
  (IAM, OPA, identity service) that the agent reads but cannot write.
  Promotions require an attestation from a different principal
  (human + hardware key, or a deterministic policy that the agent
  cannot influence). Log every promotion attempt, even denied ones.

### AS-C-DF-AGENTIC_T9-003 — Inter-agent message accepted without identity verification
- **Severity:** high
- **Category:** defend
- **Legacy ID:** TIER2-AGENTIC-T9-03
- **Languages:** any
- **Frameworks:** owasp_agentic=[T9, T5], owasp_llm=[LLM06]
- **Look for:** Multi-agent code (CrewAI `Crew(...)`, LangGraph
  supervisor / handoffs, AutoGen `GroupChat`, custom `accept_task` /
  `dispatch` / `handle_message` handlers) where one agent processes
  a task / plan / instruction from another agent without checking
  who sent it. Specifically: no signature verification, no trust
  score check, no allowlist of accepted senders, no scope-narrowing
  on delegation.
- **Skip if:** Inter-agent messages are signed (Ed25519, JWT, mTLS)
  AND the receiver verifies the signature AND a trust-threshold
  check exists before the action runs. Single-process toy demos
  (`if __name__ == "__main__"`) get a pass.
- **Why it matters:** Mirrors OWASP ASI-05 (Trust Boundary
  Violation). Multi-agent systems where every agent trusts every
  other agent collapse into a single shared blast radius — one
  compromised agent compromises every action across the crew. The
  "fellow agent" channel is the easiest privilege-escalation path
  in agentic systems.
- **Remediation:** Each agent gets its own identity (DID / signed
  token / mTLS cert). Receivers verify the sender's signature
  before acting. Delegation must narrow scope: a child task's
  capability set ⊆ parent's. Reject (with audit log) any message
  from an unknown or low-trust sender.

### AS-C-DF-AGENTIC_T9-004 — Agent identified by string name, not crypto identity
- **Severity:** medium
- **Category:** defend
- **Legacy ID:** TIER2-AGENTIC-T9-04
- **Languages:** any
- **Frameworks:** owasp_agentic=[T9], cwe=[CWE-287, CWE-322]
- **Look for:** Agent identity carried as a bare string —
  `agent_name = "billing-agent"`, `Agent(name="research-bot")`,
  audit-log `agent_id` populated from a config string with no
  cryptographic backing. No DID (`did:web:`, `did:key:`), no
  per-agent key material, no signing of inter-agent messages or
  audit entries.
- **Skip if:** The agent has a unique cryptographic identity (Ed25519
  keypair, JWK, mTLS cert) AND tool calls / audit entries / inter-
  agent messages are signed with that key.
- **Why it matters:** Mirrors OWASP ASI-07 (Insecure Identity).
  String names are spoof-trivial: any process that knows the name
  can claim the identity. Without crypto identity you can't tell
  which agent really emitted a finding, which agent really called a
  tool, or which agent really sent a multi-agent message — making
  T9-02 (self-promotion) and T9-03 (inter-agent trust) checks
  meaningless from outside the box.
- **Remediation:** Issue per-agent keypairs at provisioning. Sign
  audit entries (hash-chained) and inter-agent messages with the
  agent's key. Verify on receipt. Treat the keypair as the source
  of truth for identity; the human-readable name is a label for
  operators, not a security primitive.

### AS-C-DF-AGENTIC_T10-001 — High-volume HITL request fatigue
- **Severity:** low
- **Category:** defend
- **Legacy ID:** TIER2-AGENTIC-T10-01
- **Languages:** any
- **Frameworks:** owasp_agentic=[T10]
- **Look for:** HITL approval gates wired on routine actions (e.g.
  every read query needs approval). Reviewers will rubber-stamp.
- **Skip if:** HITL is reserved for destructive / high-impact actions.
- **Why it matters:** Approval fatigue defeats the purpose of HITL.
- **Remediation:** Reserve HITL for actions with real stakes. Use
  rate-limiting and policy auto-approval for routine reads.

### AS-C-D-AGENTIC_T11-001 — RCE via deserialisation
- **Severity:** critical
- **Category:** detect
- **Legacy ID:** TIER2-AGENTIC-T11-01
- **Languages:** java, python, any
- **Frameworks:** owasp_agentic=[T11], cwe=[CWE-94, CWE-502]
- **Look for:** `pickle.loads(...)`, Java `ObjectInputStream.readObject()`,
  YAML `yaml.load(...)` (without SafeLoader), where the input is from
  the network / LLM output / user upload.
- **Skip if:** Input is `yaml.safe_load`, JSON only, or a typed-schema
  parser.
- **Why it matters:** Classic RCE. LLM output is untrusted; if it
  reaches a deserialiser, you have a code-exec primitive.
- **Remediation:** Never deserialise untrusted data. Use JSON + schema
  validation.

